messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /api/users/{id}

All HTTP methods acceptable: false

Method acceptability (based on the code):
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- The Express app mounts the user router with the prefix app.use('/api/users', userRoutes) in server.js, so every route in routes/userRoutes.js is prefixed with /api/users.
- routes/userRoutes.js defines a route group for '/:id':
  - router.route('/:id').delete(protect, admin, deleteUser).get(protect, admin, getUserById).put(protect, admin, updateUser);
  - That corresponds to the full path /api/users/:id, converted to OpenAPI-style parameter syntax: /api/users/{id}.
- The router explicitly registers handlers for GET, PUT, and DELETE on this path, so those methods are acceptable.
- The code does not explicitly register handlers for HEAD, POST, OPTIONS, TRACE, or PATCH on this path, so those methods are marked not acceptable based solely on the source code analysis (no implicit framework behavior assumed). 
- "All HTTP methods acceptable" is false because the router does not use a catch-all (like router.all(...)) for this path.
